	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>All-Africa free-trade area proposed at G20</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>It is reported that a joint initiative at the G20 summit in Seoul by Jacob Zuma and Shriti Vadera (formerly a development minister in the UK Labour Government and now a G20 adviser) has proposed the creation of a free-trade area (FTA) covering all of Africa. The idea is part of an anti-poverty strategy which, according to President Zuma, should include major investments in infrastructure and skills development to help rebalance the world economy by creating new centres of demand outside the flagging economies of North America and Europe. It is planned to use a meeting in January of ‘the continent’s major powers’ to take forward the idea of replacing the existing free-trade areas with a single one spanning 26 countries.</p><p>The initiative was strongly welcomed by UK Prime Minister David Cameron, who expressed the hope that it would help to tackle ‘all the trade barriers that exist between African countries’. Together with the German Chancellor, Angela Merkel, he has also launched an experts’ group to look at ways to promote trade liberalisation and revive the WTO’s struggling Doha Round of trade talks. Headed by Peter Sutherland, who as Director General of GATT facilitated the final negotiations of the Uruguay Round, it also includes Professor Jagdish Bhagwati of Columbia University.</p><p>The task of the experts’ group will be to ‘assess the current environment for trade and to recommend the priority political and regulatory steps needed to increase global trade flows in the short and medium term.’ It will assess the various options for the conclusion of the Doha Round, but will also ‘define a longer term approach to trade liberalisation and regional integration in support of the multilateral trading system, including steps to tackle regulatory, administrative and physical barriers to trade.’</p><p>Yet a group of trade experts has concluded that there may be a misplaced emphasis on new<i>&nbsp;</i>liberalisation commitments in the multilateral system. ‘The biggest gains from an agreement in the Doha Round of global trade talks’, they argue, ‘ may have less to do with securing new trade-opening than with locking in the considerable reforms governments have already made.’ Organised by the WTO, the World Bank, and the International Centre for Trade and Sustainable Development (ICTSD), a Geneva-based civil society think tank, experts at the meeting emphasised the Doha Round’s value as ‘an insurance policy against protectionism’. David Laborde, for example, of the International Food Policy Research Institute, gave an estimate that if governments were to use the flexibilities from which they currently benefit in the WTO to raise their tariffs to the highest levels they had actually applied during the past 13 years (which is significantly lower in many cases than the maximum tariff they are entitled to impose), the losses to the world economy would be over $100 billion. But, if there were a Doha agreement on broadly the terms currently being discussed, it would offset the lion’s share of such losses.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>‘G20: free-trade area for Africa proposed by UK and South Africa’, press article, 11 November 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/nov/11/g20-free-trade-area-for-africa" target="_self">http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/nov/11/g20-free-trade-area-for-africa</a>&nbsp;</p><p>ICTSD, ‘Cameron and Merkel create experts group to promote trade’, article, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News Digest</i>, Vol. 14, No. 38, 3 November 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/92894/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/92894/</a></p><p>ICTSD, ‘Doha deal would lock in existing liberalisation, say experts; can members agree?’, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News Digest</i>, Vol. 14, No. 38, 3 November 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/92897/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/92897/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>When the global financial crisis was at its height in 2008, there were widely expressed fears that the knock-on economic crisis would be made worse by a retreat into protectionism by major countries. In the main it did not happen, but the danger is a constant one in times of stress. Would a completed Doha Round reduce the danger? By limiting the latitude (considerable in some cases) that the current WTO rules give members to increase their tariffs up to the maximum permissible level, it would certainly restrict one avenue for protectionism. But as global commerce evolves, so do the ways in which powerful countries can disrupt the trade of weaker states. Only if the WTO rulebook evolves as rapidly will it act as an effective brake across the board – but there is strong resistance among many members against such an extension. And a Doha deal appears as elusive as ever.</p><p>The renewed interest in regional liberalisation is not surprising. Out of the 79 ACP states, 48 of them are in Africa, and an all-Africa FTA would increase the potential gains compared to the more limited FTAs currently being discussed (see <i>Agritrade </i>article, ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Key-topics/EPA-negotiations/Regional/Eastern-and-Southern-Africa/News/Trade-policy-Eastern-and-Southern-Africa-free-trade-area-starts-to-take-shape" target="_self">Trade policy: Eastern and Southern Africa free-trade area starts to take...</a>’, October 2010) – but it would also increase the challenges. The main economic gain from an FTA is to remove barriers to trade between members with the explicit expectation that in some cases intra-regional imports will displace domestic production. This allows production in the exporting states to be increased, reaping economies of scale, but can also create tensions in the net importing states.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
